    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "f996d6e8_25cd31b1",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001907
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-29T15:31:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is true, but it starts poking into dynamic type land. For context, I think we all agree that putting giant \u0027service\u0027 objects into the context is fine; these are 1/instance. For datastore transactions, it was kind-of fine, because \"in a transaction\" wasn\u0027t required, and there was only one type. However lack of tests could definitely end you up in hot water. In this case there are now multiple types of transactions, and a transaction of SOME sort is always required (iiuc).\n\nThis definitely makes the compiler less helpful as a tradeoff for more concise code and introduction of potential runtime errors. However, ultimately, I haven\u0027t worked with spanner to tell if this tradeoff is the right one, so I\u0027ll defer to you and vadim.\n\nIdeally Go would have some sort of compiler-checked context thing, but, well... we can\u0027t have that.",
      "parentUuid": "5997dda8_667f1989",
      "revId": "9cf8dce9c5ea34498dc338ef7f334b92974490da",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cddec62d_da93ecb0",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-29T22:31:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e However, ultimately, I haven\u0027t worked with spanner to tell if this tradeoff is the right one, so I\u0027ll defer to you and vadim.\n\nI also have no first-hand experience writing code for Spanner, so I defer this to Nodir :)\n\nNote that I still need at least RW(...) transaction in the context (with Defer), or server/tq API will be very ugly (we\u0027ll need to expose an API specifically for Spanner). So far I was hoping to make server/tq to be oblivious of what transactional engine is used, and this requires all relevant guts to be in context.Context, so they can round-tripped through server/tq API to the transaction engine API.\n\nSo our options:\n1. Land this CL and risk writing panic-happy code.\n2. Land a previous variant of this CL that used ctx.RW(...) but otherwise passed `txn` explicitly everywhere.\n3. Don\u0027t land this at all and make spanner-specific variant of server/tq.\n\nWhat do you prefer?",
      "parentUuid": "f996d6e8_25cd31b1",
      "revId": "9cf8dce9c5ea34498dc338ef7f334b92974490da",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
